title: For Trade:  CZ 85 compact
postcontent:
This CZ 85 compact was a limited run from CZ in 94 and it has the low production number of 55. This is what the P06 came from.
It is chambered in .40 s&w and has a steel frame so the recoil is very minimal.
The finish is outstanding with only a little wear on the take down pin.
It comes with the factory case and test target
It has the two factory flush fit mags and it absolutely loves HD rounds! The only feed problems I have ever had was with flat nosed target rounds but I guess that is understandable because the mag springs are the old factory ones and probably could stand to be replaced.
I have recently replaced the recoil spring with a WOLFF and that is the only modifications that has been done to it.
The WOLFF spring was in a kit so those unused springs are included along with the original.  
 
I am looking to trade for a Kahr PM.40 or 45 and prefer the all black model  but am open to the stainless CM models as well.
I will also like to try the Kahr MK'S.

 
I put a trade value of $450 on it and can add cash or ammo for the right trade.
I will consider  lower cash offers but really looking to trade

This is a Pre-Ban Norinco "Sneak" M14.  One of the first M14's imported into the country. postcontent:
Selling my Rock Island 1911 .45 pistol cuz I've had fun with it, but now I have my eye on another toy, and can't afford to keep both. You know how that one goes.
The pistol's in nearly pristine condition, and has been a great shooter. It's had less than the 500 rounds through it, which is the amount of break-in firing recommended by the manufacturer, so it's basically still new.
I have the black rubber factory grips seen in the photo, but I currently have some retro-looking GI-style walnut checkered grips on it that look really good.
The Tactical model is different than their basic GI model in that it has dovetailed Novak-style sights, an extended beavertail, skeletonized steel trigger, skeletonized hammer, a flared ejection port, and ambidexterous safety.
These come from the factory with a Parkerized/phosphate finish, and I've also applied some gun-sight paint to the rear sight dots, and the front sight post (which really help).
Included is the factory ( Italian-made ACT) magazine, as well as an extra US military issue magazine.
As I said, it's been a reliable shooter, and I have no problems with a test fire if you have someplace safe and convenient to shoot (and of course, your own ammo!)
I can only sell to legal Georgia residents, over 21 years old, and must at least see a drivers license. I can sell to Ala. residents, but legally we'd have to do the FFL transfer on the Ala. side, which typically will cost you $25.
I'm a 51 year old Ga. resident, with my Ga. carry permit, so everything's good on my end.
E-mail me, or call/text 706-three-o-four-0494 (preferably both, to be sure.)
Thanks for looking........

title: For Sale:  CDM 22 Cal. Short
postcontent:
Crterion Die & Machine Co. (NCIC maker code CDM) was located on Wooster Street in Manhattan where the revolvers were manufactured and/or assembled. It's possible the small parts were imported, but that CDM manufactured the potmetal frame there. Although claimed as"American manufacture" in advertising literature, at least some parts were likely to have been made in Mexico. 

They made at least 3 different guns, a six shot 22 shot, a six shot 22 long and a 2 barrel 22mag derringer. 

New York refused CDM a manufacturing license in the early 70's and CDM lost the suit which attempted to set aside the licensing law on the basis of Federal Preemption. (C.D.M. Products, Inc. v. City of 
New York, 350 N.Y.S.2d 500 (N.Y. Sup. Ct. 1973))

The production of the gun was also effected by NY passing rules regarding the melting point of metals used in the frames of guns, which the pot metal could not meet, thus production was ceased.

CDM Prod. Inc.  New York NY  22 Cal Short SN# 336847  Finish is a little worn, especially on the cylinder. Works good...Perfect Saturday Night Special!

title: For Sale:  ASM Colt Snubnose BP .44 Army
postcontent:
Armi San Marco black powder Colt revolver that has been customized to mimic an "Avenging Angel" snubnose revolver of the 1800's. This is a .44 caliber gun based on an 1851 style revolver (yeah, not historically accurate). I checked the serial numbers and it was made in the early 80's ('83 I believe). I have not shot it extensively but I can attest it makes a nice big muzzle flare with a potent loading.

The bore is in great shape, although the inside of the chambers show some minor corrosion (surface rust, no pitting). Brass needs to be polished up to look nice but overall the gun is in great functional shape. Hammer shows some peening but nipples look great and I have had 100% ignition with it. The action and trigger are nice as is typical of Colt clones. No. 11 caps fit perfectly and it has shown good reliability for a Colt. I use .454 round balls with good effect and chamber sealing. 

Gun will come with the original full-length loading lever for loading on the gun and if you like I can throw in a bird's head grip, although I have no frame for it.
